  "original_title": "\u0d9c\u0dca\u200d\u0dbb\u0dc4\u0dbd\u0ddd\u0d9a 5\u0d9a\u0dca \u0d91\u0d9a\u0db8 \u0dbb\u0dda\u0d9b\u0dcf\u0dc0\u0d9a",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "5 planets in the same line",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "There are five planets in our solar system that can be observed with the naked eye. They are Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn. These planets can be observed in the night sky separately at different times of the year, and these days it is special to be able to observe all 5 planets in the sky at the same line at the same time.",
        "The image above shows how all 5 planets are in the same line on June 29, 2022 (5 am).",
        "Saturn is located slightly above the sky, so it may be difficult to identify the other planets, but the other planets can be easily identified by drawing an imaginary line connecting the brightest planets, Venus and Jupiter.",
        "This phenomenon can be most clearly observed in the sky from 4:40 am on Wednesday, June 29 (Wednesday), when the effect of the moon's light is minimal. This phenomenon can be observed until the end of the first week of July, if the horizon is clearly visible.",
        "As Mercury approaches the Sun after the first week of July, it will not be visible, but the other planets will remain in this linear position until the first week of August 4.",
        "If the solar system were completely flat, the position of the planets could be frequently observed in this way. But in reality, the orbits of the planets are seldom at right angles, so it is rare for the planets to appear in such a linear position."
      ],
